\section{3. Magnetic Monopoles – The Hidden Symmetry}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{3. Magnetic Monopoles – The Hidden Symmetry}

\subsection{The Problem}
Maxwell's equations would be more symmetric with magnetic monopoles, but they don't seem to exist.

\subsection{T0 Solution: Emergent Symmetry from Energy Field Topology}

\subsubsection{Standard Maxwell Equations (asymmetric)}
\begin{align}
	\nabla \cdot \vec{E} &= \rho/\epsilon_0 \quad \text{(electric charge exists)} \\
	\nabla \cdot \vec{B} &= 0 \quad \text{(no magnetic charge)}
\end{align}

\subsubsection{T0 Energy Field Interpretation}

\textbf{Electric charge} = Localized energy field source:
\[
q_e = \int E_{\text{field}} \, d^3x
\]

\textbf{Magnetic field} = Rotation of the energy field:
\[
\vec{B} = \nabla \times \vec{A} = \nabla \times (E_{\text{field}} \cdot \hat{n})
\]

\subsubsection{Why No Magnetic Monopoles?}

\textbf{Topological condition:}
\[
\oint \vec{B} \cdot d\vec{A} = \oint (\nabla \times \vec{E}_{\text{field}}) \cdot d\vec{A} = 0
\]
This holds \textbf{always} by Stokes' theorem because the energy field $E_{\text{field}}$ is \textbf{globally defined}.

\subsubsection{The Hidden Symmetry Revealed}

The \textbf{true symmetry} is not electric-magnetic, but:
\[
\boxed{\text{Energy field source} \;\leftrightarrow\; \text{Energy field rotation}}
\]

\textbf{Mathematically:}
\begin{align}
	\text{Electric:} \quad &\nabla \cdot E_{\text{field}} = \rho_E \\
	\text{Magnetic:} \quad &\nabla \times E_{\text{field}} = \vec{j}_E
\end{align}
This \textbf{is perfectly symmetric} in energy field space!

\subsubsection{Why We Don't See Monopoles}

In the 3D projection, this symmetry appears broken because:
\[
\vec{B}_{\text{observed}} = \operatorname{Projection}(\nabla \times E_{\text{field}})
\]
The symmetry is \textbf{not hidden} – it exists at the fundamental energy field level but appears asymmetric in our macroscopic electromagnetic description.

\textbf{Result:} The ``missing symmetry'' is in fact \textbf{fully present} at the T0 energy field level.

